writers -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPrimarily on the basis of ethnographic case-studies from around the world, this volume links investigations of work to questions of personal and professional identity and social relations. In the era of digitalized neoliberalism, particular attention is paid to notions of freedom, both collective (in social relations) and individual (in subjective experiences). These cannot be investigated separately. Rather than juxtapose economy with ethics (or the profitable with the good), the authors uncover complex entanglements between the drudgery experienced by most people in the course of making a living and ideals of emancipated personhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aFreedom. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aWorkxMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aPolitical and Economic Anthropology, Sociology.1 aAngé, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAwal, Akanksha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCefkin, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDąbkowska, Magdalena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGershon, Ilana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHann, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHann, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJones, Deborah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKauppinen, Anna-Riikka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenhard, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMi